Problem statement (Term Deposit Sale)¶

Goal¶

Using the data collected from existing customers, build a model that will help the marketing team identify potential customers who are relatively more likely to subscribe term deposit and thus increase their hit ratio.

Resources Available¶

The historical data for this project is available in file https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Bank+Marketing

Attribute information¶

Input variables:¶

Bank client data:¶

  1. age: Continuous feature
  2. job: Type of job (management, technician, entrepreneur, blue-collar, etc.)
  3. marital: marital status (married, single, divorced)
  4. education: education level (primary, secondary, tertiary)
  5. default: has credit in default?
  6. housing: has housing loan?
  7. loan: has personal loan?
  8. balance in account

Related to previous contact:¶

  1. contact: contact communication type
  2. month: last contact month of year
  3. day: last contact day of the month
  4. duration: last contact duration, in seconds*

Other attributes:¶

  1. campaign: number of contacts performed during this campaign and for this client
  2. pdays: number of days that passed by after the client was last contacted from a previous campaign (-1 tells us the person has not been contacted or contact period is beyond 900 days)
  3. previous: number of contacts performed before this campaign and for this client
  4. poutcome: outcome of the previous marketing campaign

Output variable (desired target):¶

  1. Target: Tell us has the client subscribed a term deposit. (Yes, No)

GitHub repository URL¶

https://github.com/GreatLearningAIML1/gl-pgp-aiml-uta-intl-apr20-SubratMuruni.git¶

The resulting data model is a imbalanced data set with class-1 at 12% and class-0 at 88%. Analysis must be done to improve the data model balance and see if class-1 % can be imporved.

1.1.2 Data pollution, outlier’s treatment and missing values treatment¶

  1. There are 10 columns which are of string/object data type which need to be converted to categorical or other data types
  2. Most columns are right skewed with Balance,campaign,pdays and Duration being skewed. Previous is heavily skewed. Scaling and Normalization may be considered on these columns
  3. The data set has a mix of ordinal, nominal and binary categoricals.
  4. Imputation must be performed to change binary to boolean. Ordinals must be replaced with sequential order. Nominal categoricals should be exposed to one hot encoding.
  5. There are no missing values and no NA or NaN values. Also, there are no duplicate rows.
  6. Balance and pdays have -ve values which can be corrected by binning
  7. Dependent variable 'Target' denotes a imbalance dataset. Operation must be performed to balance the data set or right model should be selected.

2.1 Data Model¶

Steps for creating the optimzed data model where the clients can subscribe for Term Deposit¶
  1. Change object data type into categorical
  2. Change binary categorical to boolean (0,1) for default, housing, loan and target columns
  3. Impute ordinal categorical values for martial,education, month columns
  4. Impute -ve values of Balance,Duration and Pdays by Binning for smoothing data
  5. Keep age,day, campaign and previous as it is
  6. Check that the final datatypes of all features is int or float
  7. Scaling/Normalization (if needed)
  8. Get dummies for categorical columns job, contact,poutcome
  9. Create training and testing set in ratio 70:30

# plot the confusion matrix in terms of heatmap for better visualization. 

def draw_cm(actual,predicted):
    cm = confusion_matrix(actual,predicted)
    sns.heatmap(cm,annot=True, linewidth=0.05, fmt='.2f', xticklabels=[0,1], yticklabels=[0,1])
    plt.ylabel('observed')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()

3.3.2 Conclusion regarding the best algorithm¶

  1. The problem statement is to build a model that will help the marketing team to identify potential customers who will subscribe to Term Deposit offered by the bank.

  2. This means that the model needs to predit the maximum number of potential subscribers who can be contacted.

  3. Which in turn means, that the model should lower the False negative (People identified by the model to not subscribe to Term Deposit but who in fact subscribe to the Term Deposit).

  4. This implies that the model with the lowest False Negative or highest Recall score is to be selected as the best prediction model for the problem.

  5. From the Model score comparison dataframe, it is evident that the TUNED LOGISTIC REGRESSION model has the highest recall and hence the best model to use for the problem statement.

  6. The Precision score is the lowest amongst all the models for the Tuned Logistic Regression model, as now the model is predicting to reach out to more people from the dataset.

  7. The precision score can be compared to the actual conversion rate for subscribing to Term Deposit with respect to the number of people contacted by the marketing team. But with respect to the overall data the True Positive predicted by the Tuned Logistic regression model is 8.5% which is the highest of all the models.

    NOTE: The performance metrics of the ensemble models may improve upon further tuning and may have better recall score than the Tuned Logisitic Regression Model. The conclusion is drawn from the base ensembel models which haven't been tuned.
